The temperatures at which failure occur are not necessarily below the
polynomial fit ranges; in that case, I understand that there may be
problems.  I am using the setState_HP method to fix the enthalpy, and
perform the calculation at successively lower enthalpies.

One thing that could be very useful is to implement the &quot;contin&quot;
option that would allow a better initial guess for the equilibrium
state to be provided.  Are there plans to do this in the near future?

Thanks,

James

--- In cantera@yahoogroups.com, David Goodwin &lt;dgoodwin@c...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I haven&#39;t run into this problem before. I suppose you&#39;re decreasing
the 
&gt; enthalpy by calling &#39;setState_HP&#39; first with the desired enthalpy
and 
&gt; pressure and initial composition.  I bet the problem is that the 
&gt; resulting initial temperature is so low that it is either out of
range 
&gt; for the thermo data, or causes numerical problems for other reasons.
&gt; 
&gt; Can you run the problem fixing (T,P) rather than (H,P)?
&gt; 
&gt; You might also try the new equilibrium solver, which doesn&#39;t use 
&gt; ChemEquil.  In Python, you can access it by creating a &#39;Mixture&#39; 
&gt; containing the gas phase:
&gt; 
&gt; gas = GRI30()
&gt; mix = Mixture([(gas, 1.0)])
&gt; mix.equilibrate(&#39;HP&#39;)
&gt; print mix
&gt; 
&gt; And if you want to include a condensed phase, you can do it like
this:
&gt; gas = GRI30()
&gt; carbon = importPhase(&#39;graphite.cti&#39;)
&gt; mix = Mixture([(gas, 1.0), (carbon, 0.0)])
&gt; mix.equilibrate(&#39;HP&#39;)
&gt; print mix
&gt; 
&gt; Depending on the version of Cantera you have this may or may not
work.  
&gt; It definitely works with the prerelease of version 1.6, available
by 
&gt; CVS.
&gt; 
&gt; Dave
